#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:-1
msgid ""
"A guide to using the SIP build system in Spack for creating Python bindings "
"for C and C++ libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:13
msgid "SIP"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:15
msgid ""
"SIP is a tool that makes it very easy to create Python bindings for C and C+"
"+ libraries. It was originally developed to create PyQt, the Python bindings "
"for the Qt toolkit, but can be used to create bindings for any C or C++ "
"library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:18
msgid ""
"SIP comprises a code generator and a Python module. The code generator "
"processes a set of specification files and generates C or C++ code which is "
"then compiled to create the bindings extension module. The SIP Python module "
"provides support functions to the automatically generated code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:23
msgid "Phases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:25
msgid ""
"The ``SIPBuilder`` and ``SIPPackage`` base classes come with the following "
"phases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:27
msgid "``configure`` - configure the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:28
msgid "``build`` - build the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:29
msgid "``install`` - install the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:31
msgid "By default, these phases run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:33
msgid ""
"$ sip-build --verbose --target-dir ...\n"
"$ make\n"
"$ make install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:41
msgid "Important files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:43
msgid ""
"Each SIP package comes with a custom configuration file written in Python. "
"For newer packages, this is called ``project.py``, while in older packages, "
"it may be called ``configure.py``. This script contains instructions to "
"build the project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:48
msgid "Build system dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:50
msgid ""
"``SIPPackage`` requires several dependencies. Python and SIP are needed at "
"build-time to run the aforementioned configure script. Python is also needed "
"at run-time to actually use the installed Python library. And as we are "
"building Python bindings for C/C++ libraries, Python is also needed as a "
"link dependency. All of these dependencies are automatically added via the "
"base class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:56
msgid ""
"extends(\"python\", type=(\"build\", \"link\", \"run\"))\n"
"depends_on(\"py-sip\", type=\"build\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:63
msgid "Passing arguments to ``sip-build``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:65
msgid ""
"Each phase comes with a ``<phase_args>`` function that can be used to pass "
"arguments to that particular phase. For example, if you need to pass "
"arguments to the configure phase, you can use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:68
msgid ""
"def configure_args(self):\n"
"    return [\"--no-python-dbus\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:74
msgid "A list of valid options can be found by running ``sip-build --help``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:77
msgid "Testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:79
msgid ""
"Just because a package successfully built does not mean that it built "
"correctly. The most reliable test of whether or not the package was "
"correctly installed is to attempt to import all of the modules that get "
"installed. To get a list of modules, run the following command in the site-"
"packages directory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:83
msgid ""
">>> import setuptools\n"
">>> setuptools.find_packages()\n"
"[\n"
"    'PyQt5', 'PyQt5.QtCore', 'PyQt5.QtGui', 'PyQt5.QtHelp',\n"
"    'PyQt5.QtMultimedia', 'PyQt5.QtMultimediaWidgets', 'PyQt5.QtNetwork',\n"
"    'PyQt5.QtOpenGL', 'PyQt5.QtPrintSupport', 'PyQt5.QtQml',\n"
"    'PyQt5.QtQuick', 'PyQt5.QtSvg', 'PyQt5.QtTest', 'PyQt5.QtWebChannel',\n"
"    'PyQt5.QtWebSockets', 'PyQt5.QtWidgets', 'PyQt5.QtXml',\n"
"    'PyQt5.QtXmlPatterns'\n"
" ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:97
msgid ""
"Large, complex packages like ``py-pyqt5`` will return a long list of "
"packages, while other packages may return an empty list. These packages only "
"install a single ``foo.py`` file. In Python packaging lingo, a \"package\" "
"is a directory containing files like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:101
msgid ""
"foo/__init__.py\n"
"foo/bar.py\n"
"foo/baz.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:108
msgid "whereas a \"module\" is a single Python file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:110
msgid ""
"The ``SIPPackage`` base class automatically detects these module names for "
"you. If, for whatever reason, the module names detected are wrong, you can "
"provide the names yourself by overriding ``import_modules`` like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:113
msgid "import_modules = [\"PyQt5\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:118
msgid ""
"These tests often catch missing dependencies and non-RPATHed libraries. Make "
"sure not to add modules/packages containing the word \"test\", as these "
"likely won't end up in the installation directory, or may require test "
"dependencies like pytest to be installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/sippackage.rst:121
msgid ""
"These tests can be triggered by running ``spack install --test=root`` or by "
"running ``spack test run`` after the installation has finished."
msgstr ""

